6/30/00
  Overnight test shows Bad chan problem.  FOr some reason a switch never happens
  and it never timeout!  Same old problem.  Still need to find out why.

  Removed PID remapping from DSP code.
  Reorganized ChanInfo.

  Worked out a new channel event model with JinChurn:
    ChanInfo will have two fields: winStart and winStop to indicate the
    beginning and end of current output window.
    When these fields are modified by splicer, updateWin(chanId) will be called.
    When winStart is freezed, freezeWinStart(chanId) will be called.
    When winStop is freezed, freezeWinStop(chanId) will be called.
    When exit time is fixed, but channel is still not turned off, then
    checkWin(chanId) will be called every time splice control task is evoked.
   
    Problem: will need to adjust winStart occasionally when the window size
    is larger than half of max range.

  Long weekend test:  Rel 206 (should have been 208), with DPI 1.1 overlay,
    with statmux1010.fls overlay (to solve unstable statmux problem which
    causes lots of input halts).
  Still have sticky switch problem.  Second channel stop to switch all of
  a sudden, possibly due to an old switch which nevers timeout!

  Move all audio code around dropPic into dropPic():
    At setPidGrp, startTime = stopTime = 0.
    dropPic() calls updateStartTime only when:
      - chan mode is either CHAN_FG or CHAN_BG
      - seekPcr is FALSE
      - seekDts is FALSE
      - (how about seekSeqHdr?)

  NOTE: in original dpi code, if a channel is in ON state, even if it is
        still seeking DTS, we let it pass.  We may not want to do this
        since we always need to do timebase mapping!
  

